{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a715d5f0cf3cbfa9", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tIt Takes Few to TANGO: A Quantized Distributed\n2\tModel for Binaural Speech Enhancement\n3\tZahra Benslimane ∗† , Pierre Chouteau∗ , Martyna Poreba ∗ ,\n4\tFabrice Auzanneau ∗ , Michal Szczepanski ∗ , Fabian Chersi ∗ , Romain Serizel\n5\t\n6\t†\n7\t\n8\t∗ Université Paris-Saclay, CEA, List, F-91120 Palaiseau, France\n9\t† Université de Lorraine, CNRS, Inria, LORIA, F-54000 Nancy, France\n10\t\n11\tarXiv:2607.08645v1 [cs.SD] 9 Jul 2026\n12\t\n13\tzahra-hafida.benslimane@cea.fr\n14\tAbstract—Neural network-based multichannel speech enhancement systems achieve strong enhancement performance, but\n15\ttheir computational and memory requirements limit deployment\n16\ton resource-constrained devices. This paper investigates lowprecision inference for TANGO, a hybrid distributed binaural\n17\tspeech enhancement system combining neural mask estimation\n18\twith spatial filtering. We evaluate post-training quantization\n19\tand quantization-aware training for the neural components,\n20\tand analyze how quantization errors in the mask estimators\n21\tpropagate through the downstream spatial filtering stage. Our\n22\tanalysis shows that, although quantization degrades intermediate mask estimates, the spatial filtering stage compensates for\n23\tmost quantization-induced errors. Leveraging this robustness,\n24\twe simplify TANGO into MN-TANGO, reducing both model\n25\tsize and computational complexity while maintaining comparable\n26\tfinal performance. By combining INT8 weight-and-activation\n27\tquantization with ERB compression and grouped recurrent\n28\tlayers, the most compact MN-TANGO reaches 4.65 MMAC/s\n29\tand 0.177 MB.\n30\tIndex Terms—Speech enhancement, quantization-aware training, recurrent neural networks, low-compute.\n31\t\n32\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n33\tDeep learning approaches to speech enhancement (SE) have\n34\tachieved strong performance, but they often rely on large\n35\tand computationally expensive models. This limits their deployment on resource-constrained devices, such as embedded\n36\tsystems and hearing aids, where low-latency and low-power\n37\tinference are critical. To address this limitation, a growing\n38\tbody of work has investigated model compression for neural\n39\tSE.\n40\tEarly studies mainly focused on reducing model storage\n41\tthrough weight compression. Wu et al. [1] combined channel\n42\tpruning with k-means clustering to quantize the weights of\n43\ta time-domain fully convolutional network. Similarly, Tan\n44\tand Wang [2] applied sparse regularization, iterative pruning,\n45\tand k-means-based quantization to several architectures, including temporal convolutional networks, and gated convolutional recurrent networks (GCRNs). Other works explored\n46\treduced floating-point representations. Hsu et al. [3] introduced the Exponent-Only Floating-Point Quantized Neural\n47\tNetwork (EOFP-QNN), which quantizes the mantissa and\n48\texponent separately. Lin et al. [4] went further by discarding\n49\tthe mantissa entirely and retaining only the sign and exponent\n50\tbits, achieving about 81% model compression.\n51\t\n52\tWhile these methods reduce memory footprint, they primarily target weights. Activations, inputs, and outputs often\n53\tremain in floating point, so inference may still require costly\n54\tfloating-point arithmetic. This limits efficiency on low-power\n55\thardware, such as microcontrollers and neural processing\n56\tunits, which are typically optimized for integer pipelines such\n57\tas INT8. To address this limitation, Fedorov et al. [5] proposed\n58\tTinyLSTMs, combining structured pruning with quantizationaware training (QAT) [6] to quantize both weights and activations to 8 bits, while keeping the model outputs on 16-bit.\n59\tRecent studies further showed that activation and I/O standard\n60\tQAT can be more challenging than weight quantization alone,\n61\tespecially at high input signal-to-noise ratios (SNRs). To\n62\tmitigate this effect, [7] introduced a residual correction branch\n63\tto compensate for quantization errors. This approach was later\n64\textended to source separation using a knowledge-distillationbased loss for quantization-sensitive samples [8].\n65\tDespite these advances, most quantization studies for SE\n66\tfocus on single-channel, purely neural models, leaving hybrid\n67\tmultichannel systems largely unexplored. In this work, we\n68\tshow that the hybrid neural-spatial structure of TANGO [9]\n69\tmakes it robust to low-precision neural inference. We focus\n70\ton quantizing the neural network rather than the spatial\n71\tfilter, since the neural component accounts for most of the\n72\tcomputational cost [10]. Although quantization degrades intermediate mask estimates, the downstream spatial filtering\n73\tstage compensates for most quantization-induced errors. Our\n74\tresults highlight three main findings: (i) the final spatial\n75\tfiltering stage provides most of the enhancement gains, (ii)\n76\tspatial filtering mitigates most of the degradation introduced\n77\tby quantization, and (iii) the original two-stage architecture\n78\tcan be simplified into its second stage (MN-TANGO) while\n79\tmaintaining comparable final performance. Building on these\n80\tfindings, we combine MN-TANGO with QAT, Equivalent\n81\tRectangular Bandwidth (ERB) compression, and grouped recurrent layers to obtain a compact low-compute model for\n82\tdistributed binaural SE.\n83\tII. BACKGROUND\n84\tA. Baseline TANGO Architecture\n85\tTANGO [9] is used as the baseline architecture in this\n86\tstudy. Like other hybrid SE systems, TANGO combines the\n87\trepresentation learning capabilities of deep neural networks\n88\t\n89\t\fStage 1\n90\tSTFT\n91\tSTFT\n92\t\n93\tRear R\n94\t\n95\tRear L\n96\t\n97\tFront R\n98\t\n99\tFront L\n100\t\n101\tSN-DNN\n102\t\n103\tSTFT\n104\t\n105\tSTFT\n106\t\n107\tRear R\n108\t\n109\tRear L\n110\t\n111\tFront R\n112\t\n113\tFront L\n114\t\n115\tSTFT\n116\t\n117\tSTFT\n118\t\n119\tSTFT\n120\t\n121\tSTFT\n122\t\n123\tRear R\n124\t\n125\tRear L\n126\t\n127\tFront R\n128\t\n129\tFront L\n130\t\n131\tSTFT\n132\tSTFT\n133\t\n134\tMN-DNN\n135\t\n136\tMN-DNN\n137\t\n138\tSDW-MWF\n139\t\n140\tSDW-MWF\n141\t\n142\tSN-DNN\n143\t\n144\tSN-DNN\n145\t\n146\tSDW-MWF\n147\tMN-DNN\n148\t\n149\tMN-DNN\n150\t\n151\tMN-DNN\n152\t\n153\tMN-DNN\n154\t\n155\tStage 2\n156\t\n157\tStage 1\n158\tSTFT\n159\t\n160\tSN-DNN\n161\t\n162\tSDW-MWF\n163\t\n164\tSDW-MWF\n165\t\n166\tSTFT\n167\t\n168\tiSTFT\n169\t\n170\tiSTFT\n171\t\n172\tOut R\n173\t\n174\tOut L\n175\t\n176\tSDW-MWF\n177\t\n178\t(a) Original two-stage TANGO\n179\t\n180\tSDW-MWF\n181\tStage 2\n182\t\n183\tiSTFT\n184\t\n185\tiSTFT\n186\t\n187\tOut R\n188\t\n189\tOut L\n190\t\n191\tSDW-MWF\n192\t\n193\tSDW-MWF\n194\t\n195\t(b) Inverted TANGO\n196\t\n197\tiSTFT\n198\t\n199\tiSTFT\n200\t\n201\tOut R\n202\t\n203\tOut L\n204\t\n205\tSDW-MWF\n206\t\n207\t(c) MN-TANGO\n208\t\n209\tFig. 1: Overview of the evaluated TANGO variants: (a) original two-stage TANGO with SN-DNN followed by MN-DNN\n210\tprocessing, (b) inverted TANGO with MN-DNN processing before the SN-DNN stage, and (c) MN-TANGO with only the\n211\tMN-DNN stage. In (b), the dotted lines indicate the two alternative inputs to the second-stage SN-DNN: (B † ) uses the output\n212\tof the first spatial filtering stage, whereas (B ⋆ ) uses the local reference signal.\n213\t\n214\twith the spatial filtering properties of classical beamformers.\n215\tThis hybrid design makes it particularly relevant for studying the impact of quantization on both neural and signalprocessing components. In the first stage, each ear-node independently estimates speech and noise time-frequency masks\n216\tusing a single-node DNN (SN-DNN). These masks are used\n217\tto estimate speech and noise spatial covariance matrices,\n218\tfrom which a GEVD-based [11] speech-distortion-weighted\n219\tmultichannel Wiener filter (SDW-MWF) [12] is derived and\n220\tapplied as a spatial filter. The resulting ear-specific compressed\n221\tsignal is then transmitted to the contralateral ear-node. In\n222\tthe second stage, a multi-node DNN (MN-DNN) refines the\n223\tmask estimates by exploiting both local signals and the exchanged representation. A final SDW-MWF then generates the\n224\tenhanced binaural output. The overall architecture is illustrated\n225\tin Fig. 1a.\n226\tB. Neural Network Quantization\n227\tQuantization maps floating-point values to a lower-precision\n228\tinteger representation. This reduces memory requirements and\n229\tcan improve inference efficiency, particularly on hardware that\n230\tsupports low-precision arithmetic. In neural networks, it can be\n231\tapplied both to the weights and to the intermediate activations.\n232\tIn uniform affine quantization, values are mapped from a\n233\tselected floating-point range to a finite set of integer levels\n234\tdetermined by the target bit-width. The scale controls the spacing between these levels, while clipping ensures that values\n235\toutside the selected range remain representable. In dynamic\n236\tpost-training quantization (DPTQ), quantization is applied\n237\tafter floating-point training: the layer weights are stored in\n238\tlow precision, while activations are quantized dynamically at\n239\truntime according to their observed range. In contrast, QAT\n240\tsimulates low-precision inference during training by inserting\n241\tfake-quantization modules in the forward pass. Since rounding is non-differentiable, gradients are approximated using\n242\t\n243\ta straight-through estimator, allowing the model to adapt to\n244\tquantization errors before deployment [6].\n245\tIII. T OWARD L OW-C OMPUTE Q UANTIZED TANGO\n246\tA. From TANGO to MN-TANGO\n247\tTo better understand the contribution of each TANGO stage,\n248\twe investigate alternative architectures that either reorganize\n249\tor simplify its processing stages, as shown in Fig. 1. We first\n250\tevaluate two inverted configurations, denoted as (B ⋆ ) and (B † )\n251\tand illustrated in Fig. 1(b). Both variants start with a crossnode exchange of the reference signals and apply an MN-DNN\n252\tbefore the first spatial filtering stage. They differ in the input\n253\tused by the second-stage SN-DNN: (B † ) uses the output of the\n254\tfirst spatial filtering stage, whereas (B ⋆ ) uses only the local\n255\treference signal of the corresponding node. These variants\n256\tallow us to assess whether performing multi-node processing\n257\tearlier in the pipeline improves enhancement performance. We\n258\tfurther investigate a simplified MN-only configuration, shown\n259\tin Fig. 1(c), that removes the SN-DNN stage entirely. This\n260\tvariant tests whether the first single-node stage is necessary\n261\tonce inter-node information is available, or whether most of\n262\tthe final enhancement can be preserved by combining multinode mask estimation with the final spatial filtering stage. In\n263\tthe following, we refer to this configuration as MN-TANGO.\n264\tB. End-to-End Training\n265\tThe original TANGO training strategy optimizes the neural\n266\tmask estimators using mask-level objectives. However, in\n267\thybrid neural-beamforming systems, accurate mask estimation\n268\tdoes not necessarily translate into optimal enhanced signals\n269\tafter spatial filtering. To better align optimization with the final\n270\tenhancement objective, we investigate end-to-end training,\n271\twhere the spatial filtering stage is included in the training\n272\tloop. During training, we use a differentiable implementation\n273\tof the SDW-MWF, which allows gradients to propagate from\n274\t\n275\t\fTABLE I: Model comparison with quantization scheme, precision configuration, memory, and left/right ear scores. W, A, and\n276\tI/O denote weights, activations, and input/output tensors, respectively.\n277\tMem